I have made even more research on the matter, i&#39;ve found out that `RestController` annotation makes the response header to be already written at the time when `CORS` annotation is processed, it is as if `CORS` handler cannot write what&#39;s being already sent.

So in my case, i created a filter class which will add the `CORS` headers in the response like this:

    public class HttpFilter extends OncePerRequestFilter {
    	@Override
    	protected void doFilterInternal(HttpServletRequest httpServletRequest, HttpServletResponse httpServletResponse, FilterChain filterChain) throws ServletException, IOException {
    		httpServletResponse.setHeader(&quot;Access-Control-Allow-Origin&quot;, &quot;*&quot;);
    		httpServletResponse.setHeader(&quot;Access-Control-Allow-Methods&quot;, &quot;GET, POST, PUT, DELETE, OPTIONS&quot;);
    		httpServletResponse.setHeader(&quot;Access-Control-Allow-Headers&quot;, &quot;Content-Type&quot;);
    		httpServletResponse.setHeader(&quot;Access-Control-Max-Age&quot;, &quot;3600&quot;);
    
    		filterChain.doFilter(httpServletRequest, httpServletResponse);
    	}
    }

After this, i just needed to register the filter as a `FilterBean` and then it works, though not in the way i initially wanted but it atleast gives me the results i need in order to work.

